The paper deals with game theory and the computation of equilibria, which are topics typically covered in the cs.GT (Game Theory) sub-category. The use of logit dynamics and Markov chains suggests a focus on algorithms and computational methods, which could place the paper in the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The mention of rationality and irrationality in players' behavior, as well as the use of distributions and convergence measures, suggests a connection to artificial intelligence and machine learning, which could place the paper in the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) or cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-categories. Finally, the mention of spectral characterizations and convergence results suggests a connection to mathematical analysis and probability theory, which could place the paper in the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category.
